 it to increase their stakes in the company. It is not the dividend that has just been marked down, but the previous one. It is also a mark of confidence in the company and the fact that they see potential as to where the company is headed. It is going to happen also in Unilever… already, we have seen improvements in its earnings, because also there are also foreign institutional investors in Unilever. You have seen what they are doing in Guinness, Nestle, and Nigerian Breweries- increasing their stake. Very soon, they see the numbers are also becoming attractive, and they know what they are planning for the company, they’re going to buy back the shares, but not in the manner of Dangote Cement. The majority shareholder will buy from the market and further increase their stake, just like we are seeing in Nestle Nigeria, over the past several months. Back to your question, I see potential in Unilever and the numbers have improved as of Q3, even if it could be better. PARTICIPANT 1: Yes, these companies have declared dividend and their foreign investors could not get the forex to repatriate their money, and as such, they decide to buy more of their shares and while doing so, it is announced on the floor of the exchange. Had there been no scarcity, they might have not engaged in a buyback. However, when you look at these companies- PZ, Unilever… they are manufacturing locally, alternatives to foreign and imported goods. When the cost of forex goes up, the price of the imported competitive products becomes more expensive than their own. Therefore, they have more market share, increase turnover and make more money, because people are unable to source forex to import those competing products. That is one factor that is working in Unilever and PZ. Let’s not also forget that they have done a lot of backward integration ensuring that a lot of the foreign raw materials are now available locally. If you go to the market now, the cost of most food items is very high- maize, beans, soya beans… because the industries are purchasing and competing with ordinary folks. It is good for the local manufacturers because they buy the raw materials in Naira, and the market because the competing products are now more expensive. The same applies to cement. A bag is now selling for as much as N5,000, from N2,500-N2,600 in 2020. The raw materials to manufacture cement-like limestone and others are available within the country, and yet the price is rising, which is why their turnover and profit are rising. Why is the price of Vitafoam not reacting to its wonderful result? I will advise you just wait, but I need to also look at the markdown date. There are people just waiting for the markdown date, they come in to take the dividend and go. If you entered at N21.00, just wait to see if markets will just respond to that markdown date, but if there are other opportunities you see out there, you may go for them. However, February is the markdown date, which is in another fortnight. Another thing is that Vitafoam has factors that work in its favour. There will be a pullback, after the markdown, and thereafter it will move up, because the Q1 result is coming any moment from now in this January and then if it is positive, Vitafoam will maintain that uptrend momentum to change the face of the stock, which is why I advise that you exercise patience. PARTICIPANT 1: Vitafoam is entirely different from other stocks. It is a factor of the market dynamics, helped by factors like COVID-19 (healthcare facilities’ upgrade), and insecurity leading to displacements, leading to increased demand for matrasses and other products of the company. However, the year-end for Vitafoam is September 30, and the result is released between December and January. This is a stock that has more domestic investors than foreign. A lot of individuals have mopped up the shares, reducing the float in the market, following which there is hardly a stock that has recorded capital appreciation as much as Vitafoam, except United Capital. In 2020, it gained tremendously and last year, more than 100 percent. Why, is because people have seen changes in terms of turnover, profit, and dividend growth from 70 kobo to N1.50 per share, which is over 100 percent. That delighted investors, because no company has beat the record of Vitafoam before then or after. But, Vitafoam is not the only one of its kind. I see the scenario playing out in UCap, and Fidson Healthcare. Don’t forget that Vitafoam is a manufacturing company that has no regulator. It is unlike the banks… Fidelity has shown an increase in earnings and profit, but can its directors double the dividend payout? Of course, no, because they are regulated. Unlike, Unilever, PZ, Dangote Cement have no regulator to review their financials before permitting them to release. There is a lot of flexibility in what they do, which the market rewarded with a huge price leap. 